observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
1. Require the GSO and the Inventory Committee to conduct the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts for CY 2024 as prescribed in COA Circular 2020-006;
2. Direct the GSO and the Accounting Office to coordinate and conduct the reconciliation of the physical inventory and accounting records, identify and address the nature and causes of the variances and hold responsible the designated supply officers/custodians and keep up reconciled reports at all times; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
3. review the PPE balances together with the corresponding depreciation and prepare a JEV for the necessary adjustments; 
4. record accounting entries for the recognition of PPE items found at station, if any, derecognition of lost/non-existing/missing PPEs, writing off/dropping from the books of accounts of the remaining amounts lumped under the unreconciled subsidiary ledgers of PPEs, when authorized, and present the necessary disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statements;
5. prepare the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to drop from the books all infrastructure projects which were duly transferred and acknowledged received by the recipients and end-user and ensure that these are properly recorded in the LGU books; and
6. drop from the LGU books the carrying amount of all unserviceable properties, as soon as the authority to derecognize is granted by appropriate office to bring the reported balance of the PPE account in the financial statements in order.

We recommended that the Designated Municipal GSO as head of the inventory committee, perform the following actions, to wit:
8. Conduct a complete physical count of all inventory items semi-annually, prepare and annually, prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation and to the Audit Team on or before every July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
9. Cause the preparation of the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) upon distribution/issuance of the stocks to the end users and summarize all RIS in the monthly Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for recording purposes as attachment to the JEV.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
13. Require the Municipal Budget Officer to allocate in the Annual Appropriation funds for Peace and Order (POP), as part of its POPS Plan, as required in Section 4.1.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 taking into consideration that the total amount for Confidential Funds (CF) shall not exceed thirty percent (30%) of the total annual amount allocated for the LGU's POP;
14. Assume the responsibility as Special Disbursing Officer of the Confidential Funds of the Municipality, or designate a regular/permanent employee of the municipality for that purpose;
15. Require the Municipal Accountant to submit all Disbursement Vouchers of cash advance with complete supporting documents to the COA-Audit Team Leader within seven (7) working days from release of the check, as well as the liquidation thereof in accordance of Section 6.2 of COA-DBM-DILG-GOCC-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01;
16. Approve and transmit quarterly accomplishment report on the use of Confidential Funds to the Secretary of the DILG, copy furnished COA; and
17. Ensure compliance with COA-DBM-DILG-GOCC-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 and related issuances of government oversight bodies on Confidential Funds.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
18. Record the cash advance in the books of accounts and maintain a separate subsidiary record of cash advances for Confidential Funds per Special Disbursing Officer; and
19. Record the liquidation in the books within five days after the receipt of the copy of the transmittal of documents duly acknowledged by the Intelligence and Confidential Funds Audit Unit (ICFAU) and submit the corresponding Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to the COA-ATL.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as Chairman of the MDRRM Council, through the MDRRM Officer:
23. ensure that all PPAs aligned with the Municipality’s LDRRMFIP would be implemented and completed within the timeframe indicated in the plan;
24. conduct close monitoring and evaluation on ongoing projects to identify any factor that impedes the efficient implementation of PPAs and introduce interventions, whenever necessary;
25. optimally utilize the LDRRM Fund to adequately equip the constituents in their preparation to manage disaster risks towards a resilient community in times of calamities.

5. Gather and secure all required legal documents necessary for registration such as but not limited to original deed of sale, deed of donation, certificate of titles, etc.;
6. Cause the registration and transfer the land in the name of the Municipality.
7. Municipal Assessor make representation with the processing of the Transfer Certificate of Title;
8. Municipal Accountant and GSP should provide a list of the lots under the Water works Fund for proper identification and recording;
9. Municipal Accountant should record the nine (9) lots with Tax Declaration which are in the possession of the LGU.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor commission the General Services Officer and Municipal Assessor or create a team to:
Gather and secure all the required legal documents necessary for registration such as but no limited to original deed of sale, deed of donation, original certificate of titles, etc;
Cause the registration and transfer the land in the name of the Municipality.
We also recommend that the:
Municipal Assessor make representation with the Sangguniang Bayan to appropriate funds to be used for the expenses in processing the Transfer Certificate of Title;
Municipal Accountant and GSO should provide a list of the lots under the Waterworks Fund for proper identification and recording;
Municipal Accountant should record the nine (9) lots with Tax Declaration and are in the possession of the LGU.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Separate the LDRRMF Prior Years from the General Fund and recognize it under Trust Fund book;
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for transfers of agency’s unutilized DRRMF to the special trust fund by year of transfer;
Prepare Disbursement Voucher immediately to transfer the current unexpended LDRRMF amounting ₱2,795,697.22 to the appropriate account under the Trust Fund;
Henceforth, prepare the accounting entries for LDRRMF transactions in accordance with the prescribed standards.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
issue a directive to each official of LGU-Albuera, who are responsible in the accounting and reporting of the Local Road Network of the LGU, to accomplish the procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2015-008; 
monitor their compliance thereon; and
submit to COA the correct report at year-end.

Specifically, we recommended that:

The Municipal Assessor inspect and assess the cost of the road lot component of all road network under LGU-Albuera jurisdiction using as guide the report submitted by the Municipal Engineer to the DILG.

The Municipal Engineer: 

Inspect, appraise and segregate each component of each road network of the LGU using as guide the report submitted to DILG and the list from the accounting records;  
Prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network (RPCLRN) with the complete description and cost of each road network and its component; and 
Submit the RPCLRN to COA every year-end, copy furnished the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer.

The Municipal Accountant: 

Record the Road Lot component of Municipal Road projects based on the report of the Municipal Assessor; 
Reconcile the composition of the Road Network account per books against the RPCLRN and adjust, where necessary; 
List all barangay road projects implemented by the Municipality and derecognize their costs in the books of LGU-Albuera; 
Provide the Punong Barangay and the Municipal Bookkeeper concerned with the list and cost of said barangay road projects for recording in their respective books of accounts;
Maintain the Local Road Network Ledger Cards with complete data/description of each component of the; and 
Disclose in the Notes to FS in the ensuing years the breakdown of the Road Network account.

The General Services Officer prepare and maintain complete Property Cards on Road Networks and its components and for every future procurement of the LGU.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Development Council evaluate first the proposed projects recommended by the Barangay Chairpersons before the said projects are incorporated in the Municipality’s Annual Investment Plan, including the correctness of the project cost; 

The Municipal Planning and Development Officer submit a report to the Municipal Mayor and the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) of the list of projects with delayed procurement to resolve the causes of the delay; 

The BAC Chairman speed up the conduct of bidding of the projects identified in the AIP following the schedule of implementation as indicated in the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP); and

The Municipal Engineer implement and monitor strictly all projects awarded during the year to ensure their completion within the timelines specified in the contract/agreement.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

enforce strictly the provisions of Resolution 2017-123 and the Revenue Code of Albuera through the issuance of Demand Letters to all delinquent water consumers and market stallholders; and

Discuss and resolve, with the official in-charge of AMWSS, the difficulties encountered in the operations of the water system and improve the technical services provided to problem areas so all users receive consistent and satisfactory water supply.

We also recommended that the official in-charge of AMWSS:

require the AMWSS programmer to conduct a workshop on the functions of the program used to record and monitor the waterworks transactions to familiarize the employee-users;

generate monthly reports that summarizes unpaid accounts and the delinquent payees and submit to the Municipal Accountant;

prepare Demand Letters monthly to all delinquent water consumers for signature of the Mayor; and

Issue Notices of Disconnection to water consumers who fail to adhere with the Demand Letters. 

Further, we recommended that the Municipal Treasurer: 

maintain a registry book to monitor stall applicants;

collect on the specified dates all rentals due from all market stallholders, with surcharges, if necessary; 

send monthly written notices to delinquent stallholders; and

Cancel the contract of lease of space or stall whose rental fee has not been paid for three (3) consecutive months and declare such space or stall vacant.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor convene the Market Committee and require them to:

Compute the appropriate rates for each market section that can cover all the operating costs and yield a reasonable revenues;

Update the Revenue Code of the Municipality specifically the rates, fees and charges to be imposed;

Submit the proposed revisions to the Sangguniang Bayan, with the Municipal Mayor recommending its approval.

We also recommended that the Municipal Vice Mayor, as the Presiding Officer of the Sangguniang Bayan, facilitate the immediate issuance of a local revenue ordinance for the adoption of the revised rates and charges of the Municipality.

Further, we recommended that the Budget Officer properly allocate cost of improvement, repair and other related expenses attributable to Market operations.

We recommended that:

The MDRRM Officer implement the programs and activities identified in the annual LDRRMFIP to fully equip the LGU in the preparation and management of risks and effects of disasters and calamities;

The Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, open a separate bank account solely for LDRRMF and deposit therein all the unexpended prior years LDRRMF, excluding the Capital Outlay from previous years.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor mandate the Municipal Accountant to:

comply with PPSAS 12 by recording in the appropriate Inventory account all procured supplies and materials on the month that the items were delivered;
record the related expenses only when the Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (MRSMI) are submitted by the end-users;
maintain Supplies Ledger Card for each inventory item;
determine the composition of the balances in the Inventory accounts from prior years and with proper evidences on its issuances, prepare the necessary adjustments in the books.

We also recommended that all Department Heads should:

Prepare Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) every time an item is issued from its stock and summarize the same in the Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (MRSMI);
Submit the MRSMI with the RIS to the Accountant for recording in the books.  
Maintain Stock Card for each item and reconcile the same with the Supplies Ledger Card in the Accounting Office.  
Conduct physical count of inventories every year and submit a copy of the Report on Physical Count of Inventories to the Office of the Accountant and the Audit Team.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant perform the following corrective measures:

Confirm with the Source Agency concerned the accuracy of the LGU’s liabilities as reflected in the Due to NGA accounts;

Identify which of the funds were intended for program/projects which has been completed, terminated, cancelled or abandoned in order to identify those that are due to be returned;

Submit the liquidation documents on all completed projects/programs to comply with the signed MOA and so that succeeding tranches, if any, will be released to the LGU.

We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer determine the availability of cash of all fund transfers which are reported in the books and issue checks in favor of the Source Agencies for all unutilized funds.
